<DOC><DOCNO> AP890619-0192 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 2133EST</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-Scotus-Glance     06-19 0705</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Scotus-Glance,680</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: Following originally ran as PM-Scotus-Glance a0576</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actionstaken Monday by the Supreme Court.      DRUG TESTS      The court gave railroads broader power to test their workers fordrugs, upholding routine tests for Conrail employees.   By a 7-2 vote, the justices said Conrail _ the Consolidated RailCorporation _ may require the tests without permitting collectivebargaining over the issue.   The decision marks the first time the court has ruled on drugtesting by private employers. But the ruling is based on aninterpretation of the federal Railway Labor Act and may not havesweeping impact for other workers.   The case is Conrail vs. Railway Labor Executives, 88-1.      CHRISTIAN SCIENTIST      The court turned down an appeal by a California woman facingcriminal charges in her daughter's death because she tried to healthe child through prayer rather than seeking medical help.   The justices, without comment, refused to block the woman's trialin Sacramento on charges of child-endangerment and involuntarymanslaughter.   The case is Walker vs. Superior Court, 88-1471.      BEER PRICES      The court struck down a Connecticut law aimed at assuring thatbeer sold in the state costs no more than it does in threeneighboring states.   By a 6-3 vote, the court said such laws unconstitutionallyinterfere with interstate commerce.   The case is Healy vs. Beer Institute, 88-449.      POWER RATES      The court ruled unanimously that federal courts have authority toreferee some disputes over electric power rates between publicutilities and local or state regulatory agencies.   The justices ordered a federal court to review a claim by NewOrleans Public Service Inc. (NOPSI), a utility seeking to pass on$135 million in costs to its dustomers.   The case is New Orleans Public Service vs. New Orleans CityCouncil, 88-348.      WRITER      The court turned down an appeal by Margaret Randall, a professorand writer who has been threatened with deportation from the UnitedStates for supporting communism.   The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that it ispremature to consider the constitutional and legal issues she raised.   The case is Randall vs. Thornburgh, 88-1412.      ASBESTOS      The court barred asbestos manufacturers from suing the governmentto recover money they paid to a Navy shipyard worker injured byinhaling the product.   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by twomanufacturers in a case from Washington state.   The cases are Eagle-Picher vs. U.S., 88-1382, and Raymark vs.U.S., 88-1418.      MANDAL      The court refused to reinstate former Maryland Gov. MarvinMandel's 1977 mail-fraud conviction, thrown out five years after hecompleted a prison term.   The court, without comment, rejected a Bush administration appealaimed at using Mandel's case to set guidelines on when someone maychallenge a fraud conviction for which the sentence already wasserved.   The case is U.S. vs. Mandel, 88-1759.      MARSHALL ISLANDS      The court barred additional U.S. compensation to inhabitants ofthe Marshall Islands for nuclear weapon testing there more than 30years ago.   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw out alawsuit by residents of the Pacific island republic.   The case is People of Enewetak vs. U.S., 88-1466.      LEGAL FEES      The court, in a victory for civil rights lawyers and theirclients, upheld the award of more than $4 million in legal fees tolawyers who won a Kansas City school desegregation suit.   The justices, voting 8-0, ruled that paralegals, law clerks andrecent law school graduates are entitled to compensation at themarket rate for their work.   By a separate 5-3 vote, the court said states that lose suchcases may be forced to pay extra money to civil rights attorneys ascompensation for a delay in payment.   The case is Missouri vs. Jenkins, 88-64.      POLLUTION FINE      The court left intact a fine of nearly $1 million against aMaryland paper mill operator that failed to comply with a federalclean water law's reporting requirements.   The court, without comment, rejected a challenge to a keyprovision of the act authorizing citizens and environmental groupsto sue alleged polluters.   The case is Simkins vs. Sierra Club, 88-660.</TEXT></DOC>